The paper discusses the phenomenon of increasing citations to old articles, which is a topic that falls under several sub-categories in computer science. The most likely sub-category is cs.DL (Digital Libraries), as the paper focuses on the behavior of an academic search engine. The second likely sub-category is cs.IR (Information Retrieval), as the paper discusses the metrics used to measure citation behavior. The third likely sub-category is cs.CY (Computers and Society), as the paper touches on the social implications of academic citation practices. The fourth likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), as the paper discusses the role of search engines in shaping academic networks. The fifth likely sub-category is cs.CR (Cryptography and Security), as the paper touches on the potential biases and vulnerabilities of academic search engines.
